  <h1 class="sec-h1 en">Reading Notes</h1><h1 class="sec-h1 zh" style="display:none">读书笔记</h1>
  <div class="sec-rule"></div>
  <p class="tarot-intro en">In an era where algorithms and generative models are constantly reshaping the landscape, this feeling is becoming increasingly profound for computer researchers. LLMs are getting better and better at completing language tasks, capable of generating fluent, complete, and even touching text in an instant - as if expression itself no longer requires the accumulation of experience, time, and suffering. It seems that words are gradually detaching from the human body and existing independently. But does it truly understand those themes that recur in the present and throughout human history - the tension between idealism and reality, the entanglement of love and loss, the loneliness and struggle of the individual in the world? When a model writes about "pain", has it ever experienced pain? When it describes "meaning", has it truly questioned meaning? No, it merely highly fits the expression patterns in vast amounts of text, possessing the form of language but not necessarily touching the essence of the words themselves. 
<br><br>I have always been deeply impressed by the fact that words serve as a link that transcends time and creates a resonance between people. Especially in recent years, I have been trapped in a certain sense of emptiness - meaning has loosened, many things that were once firmly believed have begun to lose their support, problems keep emerging, but it is difficult to point to clear answers. In this situation, as an individual, I am forced to confront a more fundamental truth: the world itself does not provide meaning. When the former philosophy of existence collapsed, new meaning needed to be constructed. But "construction" is not easy; it means making choices, and making choices inherently involves uncertainty and costs. However, reading presents a different dimension: the predicament, anxiety, and pain I have experienced are not isolated exceptions. Over the past several thousand years, countless people have also stood at similar boundaries, thinking, struggling, and making choices. They wrote these experiences into books, allowing later generations to recognize their own reflections in others' words. Reading is when one throws pain into the void, and those most outstanding humans respond to you through thousands of books: I hear you, your pain is valid. This is different from "为赋新词强说愁" (expressing sorrow artificially). Perhaps my shallow life experience is insufficient to support my acceptance of the universal sorrow of humanity， but this is not the trap of nihilism. Maybe the words themselves have no meaning， or perhaps there was no fluctuation when reading initially， but as experience accumulates gradually， those once silent words will reveal their original weight at a certain moment.
<br><br>
But love has always been an exception. Idealism, realism, heroism, existentialism, absurdity, cynicism, pessimism, happiness, romanticism, materialism, idealism... All these grand propositions can find echoes in the history of thought. From Nietzsche, I can see a revaluation of value; from Camus, I can read about resistance beneath the absurd; and from Sartre, I can understand the weight of freedom and choice. Countless people are called thinkers, philosophers, politicians and writers. Their viewpoints may conflict with each other, but they still form a system that can be discussed, inherited and even revised, and have gained the recognition and even support of some people.
<br><br>
But there has never been such a title as "Lover". It is not because love is not worth studying, but precisely because it cannot be summarized as some kind of universal knowledge. Everyone is trying to understand it with their limited experience, personality and circumstances. As a result, every kind of understanding is inherently biased, yet it cannot be corrected. If there really exists some unified standard that can tell people what "correct love" is, then love itself might instead become a pseudo-proposition that has been overly simplified. Therefore, love appears particularly cruel and honest, not allowing me to rely entirely on abstract ideas, nor allowing me to hide in grand narratives. I have to make choices based on my limited experience, understanding, and even with misunderstandings and deviations. And the outcome after making a choice - whether it's getting closer or losing - cannot be "explained" as right or wrong; it just happened. If philosophy deals with "how people get along with the world", then love deals with "how people meet another specific person". And the "specific person" itself is an irreplaceable and irreplicable existence. This also means that there is no truly "previous experience" in love that can be directly borrowed. I can read countless poems, novels and theories about love, but that doesn't prevent me from being foolish until now...


</p>
  <p class="tarot-intro zh" style="display:none">在算法与生成模型不断重塑的时代，作为计算机研究者这种感觉越发深刻，大语言模型越来越好的完成语言任务，可以在瞬间生成流畅、完整、甚至动人的文字——仿佛表达本身，已不再需要经历、时间与痛苦的沉淀，文字似乎正逐渐脱离“人”的身体而独立存在。可是它是否真正理解那些在当下甚至是在人类历史中反复出现的主题——理想主义与现实的张力，爱与失去的反复纠缠，个体在世界中的孤独与挣扎？当一个模型写下“痛苦”时，它是否经历过痛苦；当它描述“意义”时，它是否真正追问过意义？不，它只是高度拟合了海量文本中的表达方式，拥有语言的形式，却未必触及文字本身。
<br><br>
我始终震撼于文字作为人与人之间跨越时间的共鸣的链接。尤其是近些年，我困于某种程度的虚无——意义变得松动，很多曾经坚信的东西开始失去支撑，问题不断出现，却很难指向清晰的答案。在这种处境下，我作为个体被迫直面一个更根本的事实：世界本身并不提供意义，当曾经的生存哲学崩塌后，新的意义需要被建构。但“建构”并不轻松，它意味着选择，而选择本身就伴随着不确定与代价。然而阅读呈现出一种不同的维度：我所经历的困境、焦虑与痛苦，并非孤立的例外。在过去几千年里，无数人也曾站在类似的边界上思考、挣扎、选择。他们把这些经验写进书中，让后来者得以在他人的文字中，辨认出自己的影子。阅读就是当人向虚空抛出痛苦时，那些最优秀的人类通过成千上万本书籍回应你：我听见了，你的痛苦成立。这不同于“为赋新词强说愁”，或许我浅薄的生命阅历不足以支撑我接纳人类的万古同悲，但这并不是虚无主义的陷阱。也许文字本身毫无意义，也许初读时并无波动，但当经验逐渐累积，那些曾经沉默的文字，会在某一刻显现出它原本的重量。
<br><br>
可是爱情却始终是一个例外。理想主义、现实主义、英雄主义、存在主义、荒诞主义、犬儒主义、悲观主义、幸福主义、浪漫主义、唯物主义、唯心主义……这些宏大命题，都可以在思想史中找到回声。我可以从尼采那里看到价值的重估，在加缪那里读到荒诞之下的反抗，在萨特那里理解自由与选择的重量。无数人被称为思想家、哲学家、政治家、文学家，他们的观点或许彼此冲突，却仍然构成了一套可以被讨论、被继承、甚至被修正的体系，并获得一部分人的认同乃至拥趸。
<br><br>
但是从未有过“爱情家”这样的称谓。不是因为爱情不值得被研究，而恰恰是因为它无法被总结为某种普适的知识。每个人都在用自己有限的经验、性格与处境去理解它，也因此，每一种理解都天然地带着偏差，却又无从被纠正。若真存在某种统一的标准，可以告诉人们何为“正确的爱”，那么爱情本身或许反而会沦为一个被过度简化的伪命题。因此爱情显得格外残酷而诚实，不允许我完全依赖抽象的理念，不允许我躲进宏大的叙事中。我必须用自己有限的经验、有限的理解、甚至带着误解与偏差去做选择。而选择之后的结果——无论是靠近还是失去——都无法被“解释”为正确或错误，它只是发生了。如果说哲学处理的是“人如何与世界相处”，那么爱情处理的，是“人如何与另一个具体的人相遇”。而“具体的人”本身就是不可替代、不可复制的存在。这也意味着，爱情没有真正意义上的“前人经验”可以直接借用。我可以读无数关于爱的诗、小说与理论，但是不妨碍我愚笨至今...
</p>
